liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia's first goal scorer Emily van Egmond was trying to remain positive, after the disappointing loss to Nigeria. "Tonight wasn't our night. I think we had most possession, we looked to control the games in areas and I would love to see what the percentage of our ball retention in the opposition's final third," she said. "At the end of the day it's about putting the ball in the back of the net. Unfortunately, we were short tonight."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Matildas mull missed opportunity

children.content: Australia's first goal scorer Emily van Egmond was trying to remain positive, after the disappointing loss to Nigeria.

"Tonight wasn't our night. I think we had most possession, we looked to control the games in areas and I would love to see what the percentage of our ball retention in the opposition's final third," she said.
"At the end of the day it's about putting the ball in the back of the net. Unfortunately, we were short tonight."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: What a win. A famous win for Nigeria. They deserve everything they got tonight. They were outstanding.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: FULL-TIME: Nigeria defeats Australia 3-2 in Brisbane

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A fascinating first session of this final Test match. Australia will have been heartened to see three wickets fall, but the three dropped catches will be far less palatable - as will the 131 runs that England have scored at just over five runs per over. Harry Brook was the major beneficiary of a really poor drop from Alex Carey, piling on 48 runs in just 41 balls after being dropped on 5. Pat Cummins has bowled well, but will need to resume well after lunch or risk England getting away from them dramatically.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Lunch: England 3-131 (Moeen 10, Brook 48)
